In this context, the future of coffee production in climate change scenarios demands knowledge and proper plans (
 Baca et al., 2014; 
 Bunn et al., 2015; 
 Craparo et al., 2015), based on investments in public programs and regional management practices aiming synergies between adaptation and mitigation actions (
 Rahn et al., 2014). The perennial nature of coffee crop requires careful planning to adaptive management actions (
 Rahn et al., 2014), and alternatives must be proposed to smallholders considering local characteristics as market demand, climate, and tradition.
